comment_data.body: Given your usage below, it seems better to avoid `__init__` here and use an explicit initialisation method, e.g. `set_python_type_constructor_name()`. Then you can call that below and use `super()` for the normal constructor chain.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -4458,20 +4458,17 @@ def error_condition(self, result_code):
         return "dummy"
 
 
-class PythonTypeConstructor(PyObjectType):
+class PythonTypeConstructorMixin(object):
     """Used to help Cython interpret indexed types from the typing module (or similar)
     """
     modifier_name = None
 
-    def __init__(self, name, base_type=None):
+    def __init__(self, name):
         self.python_type_constructor_name = name

comment_data.body:
Should we maybe check if a `.type` is already set and not overwrite it?
As you may remember from past cases, I'm generally wary about newly adding options to fix special cases. Special cases are rarely special enough to break the rules.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -588,7 +588,10 @@ def declare_type(self, name, type, pos,
         if defining:
             self.type_entries.append(entry)
 
-        if not template:
+        # DW - TODO there's potentially a lot of cases where we replace the
+        # entry of a type and we shouldn't do. I'm suspicious of redeclaring
+        # entries in derived cppclasses for example.
+        if not (template or dont_set_entry):
             type.entry = entry

comment_data.body:
When I was investigating I spotted one very frequent case where `type` is re-assigned that does look intentional: `CythonScope` is recreated every time a `Context` is created and the fused types (`cython.integral` etc) have their entries re-assigned.

However, I suspect that this can't matter (much?) because it'd break parallel builds if it did.

The other option I considered was to rename the `template` argument since all `template` does is prevent the entry from being set.

So yeah - I mostly agree here, but it needs a bit more investigation to work out what simplification works

commit.message:
Improve "subscript typing" of builtins

The builtin 'list', 'dict' etc can now be subscripted in the
same way that classes in the 'typing' module can be. The entries
in the typing module are now just aliases of the builtin types.

Fixes #5033 and #4951
Add tests for subscripting builtins directly
Tweak how tests work on pure Py
Try not setting entry if it's already set
